Here's the migrated code and the key pitfalls:

## Migrated ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Code

```csharp
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // File export — return a FileResult instead of writing to Response directly
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    // Redirect — return RedirectResult instead of Response.Redirect()
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

### 1. `Response.End()` / `Response.Write()` — Gone
ASP.NET Framework used `Response.End()` which internally called `Thread.Abort()`. In .NET Core, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. Return `IActionResult` types instead:

| Old pattern | New pattern |
|---|---|
| `Response.Write(data)` + `Response.End()` | `return Content(data)` |
| `Response.BinaryWrite(bytes)` | `return File(bytes, mimeType)` |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` + `Response.Write(...)` | `return File(bytes, mimeType, fileName)` |

### 2. `Response.Redirect(url, endResponse: true)` — Gone
The `endResponse` parameter threw `ThreadAbortException` to halt execution. In Core, `return Redirect(url)` simply returns a 302 — no exception, no thread abort. **Code after a `Redirect()` call WILL execute** if you don't `return`.

```csharp
// BUG — code keeps running after Redirect():
Redirect("/login");
DoSomethingDangerous(); // THIS STILL RUNS!

// CORRECT:
return Redirect("/login");
```

### 3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` — Dead Code
Remove all `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks. They were a Framework-specific workaround. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` is not supported and this exception is never thrown.

### 4. WebForms Event Model → MVC Actions
`btnExport_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)` is a WebForms event handler. In Core MVC, use action methods with `[HttpPost]` attributes and wire up forms/buttons to POST to the action URL:

```html
<!-- Old WebForms -->
<asp:Button ID="btnExport" runat="server" OnClick="btnExport_Click" />

<!-- New Razor -->
<form asp-action="Export" asp-controller="Report" method="post">
    <button type="submit">Export</button>
</form>
```

### 5. Auth Check Pattern Change
Instead of manual `User.Identity.IsAuthenticated` checks with redirects, use the `[Authorize]` attribute:

```csharp
[Authorize]
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
{
    // Unauthenticated users never reach here — redirected automatically
    ProcessRequest();
    return Redirect("/success");
}
```

Configure the redirect target in `Program.cs`:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddAuthentication().AddCookie(options =>
{
    options.LoginPath = "/login";
});
```

### 6. `Response.Clear()` — Unnecessary
In Framework, `Response.Clear()` wiped previously buffered output. Core doesn't buffer output the same way — each action returns exactly one result. Remove it.

### Summary Checklist

- ✅ Replace `Response.Write/End` → return `Content()` / `File()`
- ✅ Replace `Response.Redirect(url, true)` → `return Redirect(url)`
- ✅ Remove all `catch (ThreadAbortException)` blocks
- ✅ Remove `Response.Clear()`
- ✅ Convert event handlers → `[HttpGet]`/`[HttpPost]` action methods
- ✅ Replace manual auth checks → `[Authorize]` attribute
- ✅ Convert `.aspx` markup → Razor views with tag helpers
